  MAJOR ASSUMPTION:-
  'PYTHON:' is the volume name assigned to the 'Drive:Drawer/' where the
  Python executable resides.

  For example:-

  Assign >NIL: PYTHON: Work:Python_1.4

  Open up a genuine AMIGADOS Shell and type:-

  AMIGA-Shell:> Python<RETURN/ENTER>
  >>> _

  AND away we go...

  Using standard syntax for Python run the DEMO scripts...

  EXAMPLE:-

  >>> execfile('PYTHON:<Path/>Coloured-Text.py')<RETURN/ENTER>

  Where <Path/> is the drawer which contains the DEMO scripts.

  These 'enhancements' will ONLY work from a genuine AMIGADOS Shell!!!

  There is a 'Python-Shell' icon and a sample Python-Startup file for
  your assistance. Just copy the icon to 'PYTHON:' and the 'Python-Startup'
  file to 'S:'...

  Copy the 'Plugins' drawer to the 'PYTHON:' volume. There should now be
  a 'PYTHON:Plugins' drawer...

  Enjoy finding simple solutions to often difficult problems... :)

  (Read the relevant files in the respective drawers for all other code in
  this archive.)

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

  AmigaDOS Error Reports When Using The RC For Data Transfer:-
  ------------------------------------------------------------

  IMPORTANT!!!, 'command' refers to the executables in the 'Plugins/' or
  'Plugins/Experimental/' drawers for this archive ONLY.

  When a command is called via Python that requires an 8, 16 or 32 bit
  data transfer back to Python the command uses the return code, RC, to
  transfer that data. This results in an AmigaDOS error report to be
  generated. THIS IS NOT A BUG!!!

  Because this error report is printed back to the screen then ways and
  means have to be applied to remove the anomaly.

  IMPORTANT NOTE:- THIS DOES NOT APPLY WHEN RUNNING 'Python' FROM A TOOL
  ICON; THIS ONLY OCCURS WHEN RUNNING FROM A SHELL WINDOW!!!... ALL
  ERRORS ARE POINTED 'EFFECTIVELY' TO >NIL: WHEN USING THE TOOL ICON
  METHOD TO START 'Python'...

  A simple means of doing so is to ALLOW this to be printed at some
  preselected part of the Python-Shell window BUT making the foreground
  and background colours the same.

  This requires two of the commands to be used in conjunction with the
  MAIN command that is required.

  1) Color:- Use this command before the 'Locate' command.
     Ensure the foreground and background colours are the same.
  2) Locate:- Use this command before the MAIN command that generates an RC
     and place the 'error' report in an unused part of the Python window.
  3) MAIN:- This is the command that uses a(n) RC to give values back to
     Python, for example 'peek 16777215'.
  4) Color:- Use this command again to refresh the foreground and
     background colours again.
  5) Locate:- Use this command again to set the print position back to
     where it was before MAIN was called.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

A Simple Python Example:-
-------------------------

ErrorHide.py
------------

# Note:- It is assumed that the 'Plugins' drawer is in the 'PYTHON:' volume.

# One way of hiding any AmigaDOS errors.
# This import is ALWAYS required!!!
import os

def main():
	# Allocate a definate value for 'rc'.
	rc = 0
	# Clear the screen for this example!
	print '\f'
	# Set the foreground and background colours the same as
        # the normal background colour.
	os.system('PYTHON:Plugins/Color 0 0')
	# Now set a print position for the AmigaDOS error report.
	# In this example the print position 15 lines down at the left
        # hand side is clear and unused so set it to that...
	os.system('PYTHON:Plugins/Locate 15 1')
	# I will do a peek of a memory location for this example.
	rc = os.system('PYTHON:Plugins/peek 16777215')
	# The 'error' WILL be printed to the screen but NOT seen!!!
	# Now issue another 'Color' to reset the colours back as they were.
	os.system('PYTHON:Plugins/Color 1 0')
	# Foreground is now colour 1, background is now colour 0.
	# Reset the print position back from where it came from.
	os.system('PYTHON:Plugins/Locate 2 1')
	# Now print the result that you want.
	print 'Value at address 16777215 is',rc,'\b.   '
	print
main()
# That's all there is to it... :)

