  Limitations:-
  -------------

  Because this/these method(s) of generating graphics and sound are TOTALLY
  NON-STANDARD I have BUILT IN limitations purely for my own reasons. As the
  source code is issued and written in what I call 'baby BASIC' then there
  is no reason why 'you' can't experiment with extending these limits.

  Any BASIC code is compiled using ACE Basic compiler.
  Any ANSI C code is compiled using VBCC or Dice-C compilers.
  Any Assembler code is compiled using a68k and linked using blink.

  All are FREE and up on AMINET for you to download... :)

  All copyrights recognised to the respective authors.

  The Limitations Are:-
  ---------------------

  1) FOR CLASSIC AMIGAS ONLY AND WINUAE/AF2005!!!
  2) Designed around Python 1.4x MINIMUM...
     NOTE:- MINIMUM, the ideas work on WinUAE/AF2005 running Python 2.0x.
  3) To be used on a STOCK A1200 MINIMUM...
     NOTE:- So long as the minimum CPU is a(n) 68EC020, any A500 with an
     accelerator card fitted will work fine but MUST ALSO have at least
     0.5MB of trapdoor SlowRam and 1MB of FastRam installed, that is at
     least 2MB of memory IN TOTAL. (A600 with 2MB ChipRam and 68EC020+. :)
  4) KickStart 3.0x and a FULL Workbench 3.0x IS required along with ALL
     standard hardware fittings.
  5) A HDD IS required, if only for convenience.
  6) OCS chipset is all that is needed for ANY graphics.
  7) Standard AMIGA 4 cahnnel stereo sound is all that is needed.
  8) The default 'Python_Enhancement' install is limited to the AMIGA
     standard 16MB boundary.
     NOTE:- ALL source code is supplied and you can alter and recompile
     the source under GPL2 terms and if your modifications work re-issue
     your experiments back to AMINET or some OTHER means of downloading
     your source code AND executables.
  9) All graphics plots are limited to a horizontal value of 1280 pixels
     and a vertical value of 1024 pixels, this should take into account
     most graphics modes.
 10) A 'SHELL' window is only capable of using the first 8 colours, that is
     palette registers 0 to 7 inclusive BUT the 'Palette' command IS capable
     of using ALL 32 OCS colour registers 0 to 31 inclusive.
 11) IF you decide on using a 'Tool' icon to start Python with then you will
     HAVE to find out which commands work and do-not work when using Python
     under these conditions; NONE of them cause system crashes but just
     don't work UNLESS they are in a 'SHELL' window. I think it is ONLY the
     'ClearScn', 'Color', 'Locate' and 'Paint' commands at the moment.
 12) The 'Mouse' command encodes horizontal position, vertical position
     and left mouse button press(ed) ONLY at the moment with a maximum
     of 0 to 4095 pixels in both directions.
 13) The 'LMB' - single click to continue - was added for easy left mouse
     button usage without the need for any special requirements.
 14) Lots of HDD 'READ ONLY' bashing will occur BUT even this is less than
     any 'Windows' TM install under NORMAL running conditions!!!
 15) System fonts of strange sizes cause odd print position 'errors' with
     relation to any graphics printed - use the system's 'SetFont' external
     command inside the C: volume to FIX the font of your choice for the
     window that 'Python' is running in. This command WILL generate a
     'clear screen' also so there is NO need to implement either a ClearScn
     command OR the Python "print '\f'," statement for this. Call the
     'SetFont' command VERY EARLY in you Python code!!!. See BELOW and in
     the archive for more information.
 16) Others that I can't remember at the moment... :)

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

The AmigaDOS 'Echo' command...
------------------------------

Echo ?
/M,NOLINE/S,FIRST/K/N,LEN/K/N,TO/K: 

Available Special Escape Codes, PLUS MANY OTHERS...

The number, "0" in the following examples, e.g. in "*e[0m" is the number
zero, not the letter O.

The hash, "#" is NOT typed as such but substituted with a number. For
example, where you see:-

  *e[#u

you substitute a number such as "40" for the "#" to give:-

  *e[40u

Apart from the "e", the letters used below ARE case sensitive.
You MUST use the case shown.

Resets        *ec     Clears window & resets all modes to defaults.
              *e[0m   Resets graphics modes to defaults.

Text Styles   *e[1m   Boldface on.
              *e[3m   Italics on.
              *e[4m   Underline on.
              *e[7m   Reverse Video on.
              *e[0m   Reset to defaults.

Text Colours  *e[30m  Text Colour 0.
              *e[31m  Text Colour 1.
              *e[32m  Text Colour 2.
              *e[33m  Text Colour 3.
              *e[3#m  Text Colour # = 4-7 inclusive if 8 colour screen.
              *e[0m   Reset to defaults.

Background    *e[40m  Background Colour 0.
              *e[41m  Background Colour 1.
              *e[42m  Background Colour 2.
              *e[43m  Background Colour 3.
              *e[4#m  Background Colour # = 4-7 inclusive if 8 colour screen.
              *e[0m   Reset to defaults.

Note - Default workbench screen colours are:-

             Colour 0  v2+ - Grey     v1.x - Blue
             Colour 1  v2+ - Black    v1.x - White
             Colour 2  v2+ - White    v1.x - Black
             Colour 3  v2+ - Blue     v1.x - Orange

Other items   *e[#u   Set maximum length of lines in window to #.
              *e[#t   Set maximum number lines in window to #.
              *e[#x   Start text # pixels from left of window.
              *e[#y   Start text # pixels from top of window.

              *eD     Move down one line but maintain current column.
              *eE     Move to start of next line down.
              *eM     Move up one line but maintain current column.

This DEMO Python script below uses the Escape Codes to change the ForGround
and BackGround colours only, but the other Codes work as well... :)

----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Python Code:-
-------------

Coloured-Text.py
----------------

# A simple method of adding 4, (to 8), basic colours to the Python Environment.
# This includes basic typefaces as well.
# The idea is copyright, (C)04-01-2007, B.Walker, G0LCU.
# It uses a standard AMIGA Shell and running Python IN that shell.
# It will only work RELIABLY this way.
# It NEEDS 'Echo' to be available in the AMIGAs PATH.
# It uses SOME of the ~Escape Codes~ available to 'Echo' to produce these
# results. In the code below are colour changes only, but any mixture
# of ForeGround, BackGround and TypeFaces can be added using this method.
# Written so that kids can understand it... :)

# This is the only import required for this DEMO.
import os

def main():
	# Ensure STANDARD ForeGround and BackGround colours.
	os.system('Echo "*e[31m *e[40m"')
	print "\f"
	print "We are going to use the AMIGA Shell to change text colours"
	print "and styles in a Python environment..."
	print
	print "This will SET Colour 2 ForeGround on Colour 0 BackGround."
	os.system('Echo "*e[32m *e[40m"')
	print "SET Colour 2 ForeGround on Colour 0 BackGround."
	os.system('Echo "*e[31m *e[40m"')
	print "This will SET Colour 3 ForeGround on Colour 2 BackGround."
	os.system('Echo "*e[33m *e[42m"')
	print "SET Colour 3 ForeGround on Colour 2 BackGround."
	os.system('Echo "*e[31m *e[40m"')
	print "\v "
	print "Now SET back to normal... :)"
	print	
main()
# Self explanatory but 'DEAD SIMPLE', Eh!

